name: Elm

values.name: declarationWith
values.comment:
If you have a specific type signature you would like you can add it here.

Note, this library will autocalculate many type signatures! Make sure `Elm.declaration` doesnt already do this automatically for you!

values.name: file
values.comment:
Build a file!

    Elm.file (Elm.moduleName [ "My", "Module" ])
        [ Elm.declaration "placeholder"
            (Elm.string "a fancy string!")
        ]

Once you have a file, you can render it using `Elm.toString`.

values.name: function
values.comment:
Declare a function. Here's an example with a let:

    import Elm.Pattern as Pattern

    Elm.function "myFunc"
        [ Pattern.var "one"
        , Pattern.var "two"
        ]
        (Elm.letIn
            [ Let.value "added"
                (Elm.add (Elm.value "one") (Elm.value "two))
            ]
            (Elm.add (Elm.value "added") (Elm.int 5))
        )

will generate

    myFunc one two =
        let
            added =
                one + two
        in
        added + 5

values.name: functionWith
values.type: String.String -> List.List ( Elm.Type.Annotation, Elm.Pattern ) -> Elm.Expression -> Elm.Declaration

values.name: moduleAs
values.comment:
A modules name

        Elm.moduleAs
            [ "Html"
            , "Attributes"
            ]
            "Html"

    will refer to

        Html.Attributes as Html

values.name: moduleName
values.comment:
A modules name

        Elm.moduleName
            [ "Html"
            , "Attributes"
            ]

    will refer to

        Html.Attributes

Note also that this will force capitalization on each segment to prevent silly errors.

values.name: pipe
values.comment:
`|>`

    Elm.value "thang"
        |> Elm.pipe (Elm.value "thang2")
        |> Elm.pipe (Elm.value "thang3")

    Results in

    thang
        |> thang2
        |> thang3

values.name: portIncoming
values.comment:
import Elm.Type as Type

    Elm.portIncoming "receiveMessageFromTheWorld" [ Type.string, Type.int ]

Results in

    port receiveMessageFromTheWorld : (String -> Int -> msg) -> Sub msg

**Note** You generally only need one incoming and one outgoing port!

If you want to vary the messages going in and out of your app, don't use a huge number of ports, instead write Json encoders and decoders.

This will give you more flexibility in the future and save you having to wire up a bunch of stuff.

**Another note** - You may need to expose your port explicityly using `Elm.expose`

values.name: portOutgoing
values.comment:
Create a port that can send messages to the outside world!

    import Elm.Type as Type

    Elm.portOutgoing "tellTheWorld" Type.string

will generate

    port tellTheWorld : String -> Cmd msg

values.name: render
values.comment: Turn the AST into a pretty printed file

name: Elm.Pattern

values.name: named
values.comment:
Elm.Pattern.named "Just" [ Elm.Pattern.var "value" ]

would result in the following unpacking

    Just value

values.name: namedFrom
values.comment:
Same as `named`, but from a specific module.

    result = Elm.moduleName ["Result" ]

    Elm.Pattern.namedFrom result "Ok" [ Elm.Pattern.var "value" ]

would result in

    Result.Ok value

values.name: var
values.comment:
A simple variable name!

This is what you want 90% of the time.

values.name: withAlias
values.comment:
This is equivalent to `as` in Elm.

Sometimes you want to unpack some stuff, but also keep a reference to the top level thing.

    Pattern.withAlias "fullTuple"
        (Pattern.tuple
            (Pattern.var "one")
            (Pattern.var "two")
        )

results in

    ((one, two) as fullTuple)

name: Elm.Type

values.name: alias
values.comment:
A custom type declaration.

    Elm.Type.alias "MyAlias"
        (Elm.Type.record
            [ ( "one", Elm.Type.string )
            , ( "two", Elm.Type.int )
            ]
        )

Should result in

    type alias MyAlias =
        { one : String
        , two : int
        }

values.name: custom
values.comment:
A custom type declaration.

    Elm.Type.custom "MyType"
        [ ( "One", [] )
        , ( "Two", [ Elm.Type.list Elm.Type.string ] )
        ]

Should result in

    type MyType
        = One
        | Two (List String)
values.type: String.String -> List.List ( String.String, List.List Elm.Type.Annotation ) -> Elm.Type.Declaration
